  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Duplexes and dual occupancy properties in Brisbane's inner east are among the more complex assets to sell well. The complexity does not come from the marketing, which is straightforward once the strategy is right, but from the decisions that need to be made before the campaign launches. Whether to sell as a whole or in separate lots, how the property is valued relative to standard homes, which buyer profiles to target, and how to manage existing tenants through a campaign all require deliberate thought. Owners who work through these questions before listing consistently achieve better results than those who treat a duplex like a standard residential sale and hope for the best.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between a duplex, dual occupancy and dual key</h2>
      <p>These terms are used interchangeably in marketing, but they have distinct meanings that affect title, financing, and buyer options.</p>

      <p>A <strong>duplex</strong>, in the Queensland context, typically refers to a building containing two separate dwellings on a single lot of land, each with its own entrance and facilities, under a single Torrens title. Both dwellings are owned together. You cannot sell them separately without first subdividing the lot or registering a community title scheme (which creates two lots within the same parcel).</p>

      <p>A <strong>dual occupancy</strong> property is broader in definition. It includes duplexes but also covers other configurations where two dwellings exist on one lot, including properties with a primary dwelling and an approved secondary dwelling (which Brisbane City Council may approve on lots meeting certain minimum sizes under its planning scheme). The key variable is always whether the two dwellings sit under a single title or have been separated into individual lots.</p>

      <p>A <strong>dual key</strong> property is often used to describe a configuration within a single building where two living spaces share a connecting door that can be locked, creating a feeling of separation without full structural independence. These are common in new townhouse developments and are typically on a single lot. They function like a duplex for lifestyle purposes but are sold as a single title property.</p>

      <p>Understanding which category your property falls into is the starting point for every other decision, because it determines what your selling options actually are.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Whether to sell the whole duplex or individual lots</h2>
      <p>If your duplex sits under a single Torrens title, you can only sell it as one property unless you first subdivide into two separate lots. Subdivision in Brisbane requires a development application to Brisbane City Council, a plan of survey, and registration with Titles Queensland. The process typically takes several months and involves council, a surveyor, and your solicitor. Whether it is worth doing depends on the numbers.</p>

      <p>The case for selling as a whole is simplicity and speed. A whole-of-duplex sale can proceed without any planning approvals or surveying, attracts investors who want a single income-producing asset, and avoids the holding costs and delay of the subdivision process. For sellers who need to transact within a defined timeframe, selling whole is almost always the right choice.</p>

      <p>The case for subdividing first is that selling two individual lots separately often achieves a higher combined price than selling the whole. This is because each lot is more accessible to a broader buyer pool: an individual duplex unit can be financed on standard residential mortgage terms, whereas some lenders treat whole-of-duplex purchases as commercial or semi-commercial lending, which carries higher rates and lower loan-to-value ratios. Subdividing also allows each buyer to build equity in their own lot independently. However, the time, cost, and uncertainty involved in the development application process means the theoretical premium from subdivision does not always materialise after those costs are deducted.</p>

      <p>The right answer depends on your specific property: the lot dimensions, the existing structure, the likely subdivision approval timeframe in your area, and what comparable whole-duplex and individual-lot sales in the suburb suggest about the actual price gap. An experienced agent and a town planner can give you a realistic assessment before you commit to a path.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How dual occupancy properties are valued</h2>
      <p>Valuers approach duplexes differently to standard residential properties. The primary method is the capitalisation of income approach, where the combined market rent from both dwellings is capitalised at a market yield to produce a gross value. This is then cross-checked against comparable sales of similar dual occupancy properties in the suburb and price bracket.</p>

      <p>The challenge is that comparable duplex sales are often less frequent than comparable house sales, which gives valuers less direct evidence to work from. Where the evidence base is thin, valuers can be conservative, and formal valuations for whole-of-duplex properties sometimes come in below what motivated buyers will pay at auction when genuine competition exists. This gap between formal valuation and auction result is more pronounced in inner-east Brisbane suburbs with strong underlying land values, where the income stream adds to an already valuable land asset.</p>

      <p>For sellers, the practical implication is that a lender-driven buyer whose finance approval is tied to a formal valuation may have their borrowing constrained by a conservative valuation figure. Cash buyers and buyers using equity from existing properties are less exposed to this risk, which is one reason investor buyers often perform well in duplex campaigns.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The buyer pool: investors versus owner-occupiers</h2>
      <p>Most whole-of-duplex purchasers in Brisbane's inner east are investors or multigenerational owner-occupiers. Pure investors want a well-tenanted asset with strong yield and a straightforward path to ongoing income. They will scrutinise the tenancy terms, the quality of the current tenants, the property management setup, and the maintenance history. A duplex with both sides tenanted on current-market leases and well-maintained common areas is a clean, low-risk asset for this buyer profile.</p>

      <p>Multigenerational owner-occupiers intend to live in one side and have a family member in the other, or to occupy both sides by vacating one tenancy over time. They are motivated by lifestyle as well as yield and often pay a premium because the alternative, buying two separate properties in the same suburb, is significantly more expensive in total. These buyers are more sensitive to the layout and quality of each dwelling and less focused on yield calculations.</p>

      <p>Owner-occupiers who intend to live in one side and rent the other are a third profile, particularly common for buyers upgrading from units to a more substantial asset. They bring genuine emotion to the purchase decision alongside the financial logic, which can make them competitive bidders at auction.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Tenancy considerations when selling an occupied duplex</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, a tenant has a right to quiet enjoyment of the property regardless of whether it is listed for sale. You cannot end a periodic tenancy simply because you want to sell, though you can choose not to renew a fixed-term tenancy when it expires. If your duplex has one or both sides tenanted, those tenancies continue through the sale and bind the incoming owner.</p>

      <p>For investor buyers, this is usually not a problem and can be a positive: a property with both sides currently tenanted and income flowing from settlement is straightforward to acquire. For owner-occupier buyers, it may mean they need to wait until one tenancy expires before they can move in, which can affect their decision to offer, or the terms they are prepared to offer on.</p>

      <p>If you are selling a duplex with existing tenants, your agent will need to manage the inspection process carefully. Tenants must be given the required notice for inspections under Queensland's Residential Tenancies and Rooming Accommodation Act (typically 24 to 48 hours depending on the type of inspection), and repeated inspections can create friction with tenants who would prefer not to be disrupted. A clear communication plan with tenants at the start of the campaign makes the process significantly smoother.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Body corporate versus freehold title: implications for sellers</h2>
      <p>If your duplex has been formally separated into two lots through a community title scheme (body corporate), each lot has its own title and potentially its own set of body corporate obligations. Sellers of body corporate lots must disclose the body corporate levies, provide the buyer with access to body corporate records, and ensure that any outstanding levies are paid at settlement.</p>

      <p>Buyers of individual lots within a community title scheme will factor body corporate costs into their serviceability calculations, and high levies can reduce what buyers are willing and able to pay. Before listing, confirm whether there are any outstanding levies or upcoming special levies relating to capital works, as these will need to be disclosed and may affect your net proceeds.</p>

      <p>For a freehold single-title duplex, there is no body corporate, which simplifies the transaction but also means the incoming owner is responsible for maintaining both dwellings entirely. Buyers will factor this into their assessment of the property's ongoing costs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Marketing strategies that work for dual occupancy properties</h2>
      <p>A duplex campaign should lead with the income story without losing the lifestyle angle. The headline and key metrics (combined rent, combined floor area, individual room counts for each dwelling) should be front and centre in the listing. Buyers who are searching for dual occupancy properties are typically making a deliberate financial decision and want to be able to run the numbers quickly. Burying the income information in the description body, or omitting it entirely in favour of lifestyle language, filters out the very buyers who are most motivated.</p>

      <p>Photography needs to cover both dwellings properly, including each kitchen, each living area, and each bedroom configuration. A floor plan showing both dwellings on the same page, with each dwelling clearly labelled, is essential. Video content that shows the separate entrances and the site layout is worth producing for a duplex campaign, as buyers often need to understand the physical separation of the two dwellings before they will commit to inspecting.</p>

      <p>The method of sale for a Brisbane inner-east duplex is usually auction, which suits the dual buyer pool well. Investors and multigenerational buyers have different motivations and different price ceilings, and auction allows competitive tension between them without either group knowing exactly where the other is positioned. A well-run duplex auction in a strong suburb will typically produce a result that exceeds what either buyer profile would have negotiated to in a private treaty process.</p>

